```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

char *getLine(FILE *f)
{
    char buffer[1024];
    fgets(buffer, sizeof(buffer), f);
    char *line = malloc(strlen(buffer) + 1);
    strcpy(line, buffer);
    size_t pos = strcspn(line, "\n");
    line[pos] = '\0';
    return line;
}
```

This function reads a line from the file using `fgets`, which includes the newline character if it's present. It then allocates memory for the resulting line and copies the contents of the buffer to it, stripping the newline character using `strcspn`. The resulting string is returned. Note that this implementation assumes that the maximum line length is 1024 characters, which should be sufficient for most use cases. If you need to handle longer lines, you may need to adjust the buffer size.

