To properly shutdown a Linux system, you should call the `exit()` function with a non-zero status code to indicate an error or a specific error code, followed by a call to `_exit()` or `exit_group()` to actually terminate the process. Here's the complete code:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <unistd.h>

int main() {
    // Your code here

    // Shutdown
    int status = EXIT_FAILURE; // Set the exit status
    _exit(status); // Terminate the process immediately
}
```

In this example, `EXIT_FAILURE` is a constant defined in `stdlib.h` to indicate a failure or error. You can replace it with a specific error code or `EXIT_SUCCESS` to indicate success. The `_exit()` function is a faster way to terminate a process immediately, without running any cleanup handlers or destructors. Alternatively, you can use `exit_group()` to terminate the current process and all its child processes simultaneously.

Note that calling `exit()` without a status code will use the value of `EXIT_SUCCESS` by default, and calling `_exit()` or `exit_group()` without a status code will use the value of the `status` variable or `EXIT_FAILURE`, respectively.

